For me, PTSD is..  It is not a pet that I keep around and feed when I need attention.  PTSD is a clinical definition ,for me (of me?), that defines the way I respond to various stimuli.  It gives a name to things that produced behaviors that I couldn't or wasn't capable of dealing with.<br><br>
The definition PTSD provides me understanding.  Shows me how to modify my behavior so to make me acceptable in society.  PTSD definition provides a handle with which I can pull myself to a better place.. Both mentally and physically.<br>
I don't need it.  But I will probably deal with it the rest of my life.  It is a mirror darkley through which I look.  <br>
To answer one of Cook's question. Do I need to suffer from this.  No, I don't need to, but I do.  Can I be cured?  Don't know.  Can I get better? Yep. <br>
 <br>
Imagine going to bed this evening and at 3 a.m. being awakened by the smoke alarm.  You lose your house and all it's contents.  A friend puts you up for the next evening.  At 3 a.m. the smoke alarm goes off and you and your friend escape with your lives.  All else is lost.  Now do that every night for 365 days.  Live at that level of adrenaline pumping expectation.  See how your outlook on life changes. PTSD..  Like Art says  &quot;The gift that keeps on giving&quot;. <br>
 <br>
Many of us were fortunate enough to be able to convert our &quot;survival skills&quot; to coping skills.  Some of us were stronger. Some of us had outlets.  Some of us had a support groups. Be that family, religion, or cultural.  Those support groups listened.  Helped, healed, understood. <br><br>
 Like most vets who have been diagnosed with this disorder, I don't need a cure; I don't need a fix; I don't need an end....  I just want someone to listen...I just want someone to care...I just want someone to recognize me and the sacrifices that were made..<br><br>
And it is a damned shame that that only comes from my brothers in arms.<br><br>
So, Cook, I envy you your strength.  I envy you your sureness and direction in life.  I envy you your peace.  I envy you  your ability to remember names, places, events.  For me that is like an event so far removed from who and what I am today, that I long for, ache for, cry for the ability to recall so that I may say goodbye and put those things behind me. So you see, Cook, it is indeed, for me a spiritual and mental problem.<br><br>
So, gettin' better.  Driving on.
